commit_message:
Implement basic policy module in code

This change prepares the magnum project to start implementing
policies in code. Subsequent patches will register more magnum
policies in code and remove the corresponding entry from the
policy file maintained in source.

This is part of a community effort to provide better user
experience for those having to maintain RBAC policy. More
information on this effort can be found below:
https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/queens/policy-in-code.html

Change-Id: I0e2b34067ea1e4d5868df544a9f65ae3f1944c43
Co-authored-By: Dai Dang-Van <daidv@vn.fujitsu.com>
Implements: blueprint policy-in-code

commit_message:
Initial OSA zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: Ie13dab5148bce17cbe0c19903918e73293e7426e

commit_message:
devstack: install Gnocchi using pip

change to continue testing 3.1.x
- use file instead of redis since it don't exist
- steal uwsgi setup from devstack master

and Migrate to Zuul v3

Migrate all functional jobs and gate to zuul v3.
We will have to migrate all other legacy jobs too later.
This patch do step 1 in the docs: Move Legacy Jobs to Projects.

diff:
- do not port elasticsearch check
- remove jobs unrelated to branch
- cleanup telemetry-integration gate
Change-Id: Idf49c523c1d0632e8d095e4804817e7b5e772902
(cherry picked from commit cc7950c86fed77e3395504530ac5dd116b4b4e5b)

Change-Id: I55193f2e39a41fe2bb378b4380f2ae52c5685c8d
(cherry picked from commit 898117902437cded9d8150ffa42869a02e3765d8)

commit_message:
Zuul-v3: add required projects for neutron-lib periodic jobs

Before moving away from the legacy/deprecated way of doing things,
bring sanity back to periodic runs for neutron-lib related projects.

This is step 1 of 2 (#2 to fix Grafana).

Depends-on: Ic05f2f9484af05b2b2d0fe143e0bb87700e116fd
Change-Id: I2950d41887b9820e9e4785650c3743792e5c73c3

commit_message:
Add more settings to glance-api

Settings added:
- limit_param_default, The default number of results to return
  for a request.
- api_limit_max, Maximum number of results that could be returned
  by a request.

Change-Id: I5362e2b15531df1d2160b67ce2b572c64b1b0989
Co-Authored-By: Alex Schultz <aschultz@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit ebbac230d19ca50658fbd8d05eae08fa6186e1b6)

commit_message:
Add gophercloud to the list of SDKs

Also, Split SDK list into openstack and multi-cloud: OpenStack specific
SDKs and multi-cloud abstraction SDKs are different beasts. Let's group
them for clarity. Also, reindented because tracking div opens and closes
was confusing since some of the divs didn't indent.

Change-Id: I2df85822ede469589e9a56ca3772828e576e549c

commit_message:
Swap the order of libcloud and shade in Python

Let's lead with our own lib which is OpenStack specific, then go with
libcloud which is multi-cloud.

Change-Id: I55de2cfd58c5bac9b694af1b9f683c03c22f7207

commit_message:
Split SDK list into openstack and multi-cloud

OpenStack specific SDKs and multi-cloud abstraction SDKs are different
beasts. Let's group them for clarity.

Also, reindented because tracking div opens and closes was confusing
since some of the divs didn't indent.

Change-Id: I20172bcd19f52d627109838e48e6a6d0727b6604

commit_message:
Add external deployment tasks executed on undercloud

Services can define external_deploy_tasks, which are meant to be
executed on the undercloud node. They are step-based as the other
Ansible tasks we have, and they get executed during each deployment
step before the puppet and docker tasks.

These tasks can be used to perform complex actions from the
undercloud, such as executing nested installers like kubespray or
ceph-ansible. This should allow deploying overcloud with a single
Ansible playbook, and without creating Ansible->Mistral->Ansible loop.

Implements: blueprint ansible-config-download
Change-Id: I3dcafb96f5cea5fdcebe2b2012b61a38b0568834
Depends-On: I8491540edf78711f3229eabeda22a17cd55e99c8

subject: Allow processing external_deploy_steps_tasks

commit_message:
Allow processing external_deploy_steps_tasks

Process external_deploy_steps_tasks as a part of config download
mechanism, which will allow services to export Ansible tasks to be
executed on undercloud directly, with full undercloud and overcloud
inventory available.

These tasks can be used to perform complex actions from the
undercloud, such as executing nested installers like kubespray or
ceph-ansible. This should allow deploying overcloud with a single
Ansible playbook, and without creating Ansible->Mistral->Ansible loop.

Implements: blueprint ansible-config-download
Change-Id: I8491540edf78711f3229eabeda22a17cd55e99c8

> So this seems fine, and I'm happy for it to land as-is when CI is
 > passing, but FWIW my original plan was to refactor all-the-things
 > into deploy-steps.j2 which would remove the need for this coupling
 > between the ansible layer and the heat software config stuff.
 > 
 > I guess we can still look at that as a future cleanup and go with
 > this in the meantime.

care to elaborate on that plan at all?

not trying to push something different to what you had planned. my goal is merely work towards 100% ansible driven for software config/changes on nodes (other than what might be driven by cloud-init I suppose).

The current state of refactorings in deploy-steps (modulo this work) doesn't get us that afaict. Particularly with our advertised interfaces. I don't even understand how we can recommend anyone to use deploy-steps via ansible without honoring our contract around PostConfig or ExtraConfigPost.

Even for upgrades to Pike, I don't fully grasp how just using deploy-steps gets us there, as there is no mechanism in place to trigger our contractual interfaces around things that happen post deploy-steps."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2017-10-17 16:12:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

> The current state of refactorings in deploy-steps (modulo this work) doesn't get us that afaict. Particularly with our advertised interfaces. I don't even understand how we can recommend anyone to use deploy-steps via ansible without honoring our contract around PostConfig or ExtraConfigPost.

Yeah you are right, but what has landed so far is just a first-pass.  I was thinking we could rework the host_prep stuff here:

https://github.com/openstack/tripleo-heat-templates/blob/master/common/deploy-steps.j2#L185

into the deploy_steps_tasks.yaml or deploy_steps_playbook.yaml, then look at how we move the per-node configuration like writing hieradata and running os-net-config.

You are right to say we need a shim to enable the heat-centric ExtraConfig stuff to keep working, and this does provided that which is great, I'm just keen to ensure we keep looking for ways to incrementally rework things into a more "pure ansible" model, which I think long term is what operators may prefer.

To clarify, I think this hybrid approach is fine as a transitional thing, but it'd be cool if we could also continue looking for refactoring opportunities to clean up the ansible workflow and make it easier to understand (deploy_steps_tasks.yaml was my attempt at doing that for the deploy steps, but clearly there's more work to do for the other configuration things we do)


Even for upgrades to Pike, I don't fully grasp how just using deploy-steps gets us there, as there is no mechanism in place to trigger our contractual interfaces around things that happen post deploy-steps.'}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2017-10-17 17:43:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

could be my own ignorance here...I gather that deploy_step_tasks are not executed via ansible for the upgrade to Pike?

Regardless, I don't think we can advertise deploy_step_tasks as a "thing" until ExtraConfigPost resources are also applied via ansible (unless just for dev/test).'}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2017-10-17 17:50:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

 > 
 > into the deploy_steps_tasks.yaml or deploy_steps_playbook.yaml,
 > then look at how we move the per-node configuration like writing
 > hieradata and running os-net-config.
 > 
 > You are right to say we need a shim to enable the heat-centric
 > ExtraConfig stuff to keep working, and this does provided that
 > which is great, I'm just keen to ensure we keep looking for ways to
 > incrementally rework things into a more "pure ansible" model, which
 > I think long term is what operators may prefer.
 > 
 > To clarify, I think this hybrid approach is fine as a transitional
 > thing, but it'd be cool if we could also continue looking for
 > refactoring opportunities to clean up the ansible workflow and make
 > it easier to understand (deploy_steps_tasks.yaml was my attempt at
 > doing that for the deploy steps, but clearly there's more work to
 > do for the other configuration things we do)

Yes, I do agree I see this as a stepping stone to something more grand. Whether that is a full switch to more native Ansible tasks embedded in tripleo-heat-templates for the per-server deployments (akin to deploy_step_tasks)...or perhaps something else entirely.

I say "something else entirely" because just by the time we finished all the refactorings necessary to switch to all native Ansible tasks in tripleo-heat-templates (as well as requiring all users to update custom resources), I wonder where we'd be at with the tripleo-apb/k8s plan and if those 2 plans are fully aligned.

What I've done here hits most of the "checkboxes" of what operators have been asking for in terms of being ansible driven, so I do think it's a step in the right direction. Also, it gets us there with very little changes to tripleo-heat-templates, which is nice for the short term (can be completely opt-out, with no disruption or risk due to task rewrite).

I'm certainly open to seeing this evolve into whatever longer term plans may come into focus.'}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2017-10-17 21:52:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 13.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2017-10-18 07:13:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

https://github.com/openstack/tripleo-heat-templates/blob/master/common/deploy-steps.j2#L402

[{'created': '2017-09-28 14:38:17.000000000', 'message': 'Config download support for all deployments

Presently, "openstack overcloud config download" only supports the
OS::HeatSoftwareDeploymentGroup (plural) resources from
deploy-steps.yaml.

This patch adds support to the command to also pull the deployment
resources for each individual server from the OS::Heat::Value resources
called "TripleODeployment", as well as other SoftwareDeploymentGroup
resources not from deploy-steps.j2. See the Depends-On
tripleo-heat-templates patch for how these resources are mapped.

These deployments are applied by additional plays in the generated
playbooks. Instead of having to reimplement each deployment in a native
group:ansible, the ansible tasks just trigger the deployments by calling
55-heat-config remotely with the rendered json deployment data for
whatever deployment is being applied.

This method saves us from having to migrate all these resources to
native ansible (and requring all end users to do so).

Also included is a helper script called tripleo-config-download to run
the config download outside of Mistral.

Change-Id: I7d7f6b831b8566390d8f747fb6f45e879b0392ba
Depends-On: Ic2af634403b1ab2924c383035f770453f39a2cd5

commit_message:
Config download support for all deployments

Presently, "openstack overcloud config download" only supports the
OS::HeatSoftwareDeploymentGroup (plural) resources from
deploy-steps.yaml.

This patch adds support to the command to also pull the deployment
resources for each individual server from the OS::Heat::Value resources
called "TripleODeployment", as well as other SoftwareDeploymentGroup
resources not from deploy-steps.j2. See the Depends-On
tripleo-heat-templates patch for how these resources are mapped.

These deployments are applied by additional plays in the generated
playbooks. Instead of having to reimplement each deployment in a native
group:ansible, the ansible tasks just trigger the deployments by calling
55-heat-config remotely with the rendered json deployment data for
whatever deployment is being applied.

This method saves us from having to migrate all these resources to
native ansible (and requring all end users to do so).

Also included is a helper script called tripleo-config-download to run
the config download outside of Mistral.

implements: blueprint ansible-config-download
Change-Id: I7d7f6b831b8566390d8f747fb6f45e879b0392ba
Depends-On: Ic2af634403b1ab2924c383035f770453f39a2cd5

commit_message:
Add /etc/environment to flannel/etcd/kubelet

Everything is containerized in rkt. If behind proxy, flannel, etcd
and kubelet will failed to rkt fetch images and cluster creation
will failed.

Closes-Bug: #1689618

commit_message:
Update keystone auth_uri and auth_url

Update keystone auth_uri and auth_url in zun.conf to connect with keystone
using /identity/v3 and /identity_admin/v3.

Closes-Bug: #1692576
Change-Id: Ie107e6ef9d3ebfee77b4782842e1ed966738c6cd

commit_message:
Allow to configure max-age for HSTS(HTTP Strict Transport Security)

HSTS is helpful to bring more protection to users, but on the other
hand, it locks down users to use HTTPS only until max-age expires. To
enable HSTS, admins must enable enforce-ssl option and set non-zero
value to hsts-max-age-seconds explicitly.

Content Security Policy (CSP) is not enabled this time. Horizon upstream
may need some work: https://bugs.launchpad.net/horizon/+bug/1618024

Change-Id: I7fd774ba9a1c292d51625d6d36a086b2a531ae75
Partial-Bug: #1713202

commit_message:
Fix post gate hook to accommodate for new os-testr

New os-testr uses stestr under the hood, which creates .stestr but not
.testrepository directory in the current dir. Other than that, it
doesn't seem like there is any difference in the format or names of
files generated in the directory.

Closes-bug: #1716746
Change-Id: Id8e7b7c678990d0b8d3f24f349800a8765206fa0

messages:
[{'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2017-10-11 19:22:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2017-10-11 19:22:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

I will want to wait to merge this until we land a patch in whereto to trigger doc publishing there.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2017-10-11 19:26:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

this change does not change publishing - it removes an unused definition.

so, it's a pure cleanup. The change is correct - not giving a +1 since the commit message does not fit what it does"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2017-10-11 19:40:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> this change does not change publishing - it removes an unused
 > definition.
 > 
 > so, it's a pure cleanup. The change is correct - not giving a +1
 > since the commit message does not fit what it does

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-15 14:14:07.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] disk-usage refactoring

The current implementation of disk usage computation was done
with exactly one partition in mind.  The computed result does
not make much sense in an environment of various level of block
devices with possible many mount points.

Currently the usage is computed at the wrong place: after the
computation some packages are installed like grub and all the
dependencies.

This patch adds a dib-disk-usage tool which scan and computes
the image just before the umount - also based on the file
systems that are created in the image.

Currently it only logs the information.  Later patches can pick
up the results and automatically adapt partition or LVM sizes.

The scan and computation takes less than 0.2 sec for a typical
minimal image.

ToDo:
* More / better comments in python tool
* test cases

Change-Id: I493d6934b95d5f9e3a2a7cbf94b18bfa00df265c
Signed-off-by: Andreas Florath <andreas@florath.net>

commit_message:
[WIP] disk-usage refactoring

The current implementation of disk usage computation was done
with exactly one partition in mind.  The computed result does
not make much sense in an environment of various level of block
devices with possible many mount points.

Currently the usage is computed at the wrong place: after the
computation some packages are installed like grub and all the
dependencies.

This patch adds a dib-disk-usage tool which scan and computes
the image just before the umount - also based on the file
systems that are created in the image.

Currently it only logs the information.  Later patches can pick
up the results and automatically adapt partition or LVM sizes.

The scan and computation takes less than 0.2 sec for a typical
minimal image.

ToDo:
* More / better comments in python tool
* test cases

Change-Id: I493d6934b95d5f9e3a2a7cbf94b18bfa00df265c
Signed-off-by: Andreas Florath <andreas@florath.net>

commit_message:
use addr pairs api def from lib

The allowed address pairs extension's API definition was rehomed into
neutron-lib with I7958a2d6f470f088ca2cb8ad638c075788f22851 and will be
consumed in neutron with I46cfeee9711973ec15881c8dc2bd0bf763bc2226

This patch switches the code over to use lib's version rather than
neutrons.

Change-Id: I40ab2abfe625c98b5506cc849ab489f68b375a06

commit_message:
Add memcache backend

Install and configure memcached on the keystone units and configure
keystone to use the cache. This should speed up token access for
existing tokens.

Change-Id: I26af0a97660e5bbe293a32e6b9e3d209338f905a
Closes-Bug: #1722541

Error logs in api_nb were missing information

Instead of the actual object id, a non-existing object with the name id was
sent to the log.

commit_message:
Requirements propose_updates runs master only

In v2 we run this only on master since the stable tree requirements are
frozen. Fix this for v3 set up.

Change-Id: I6755e4dfb050c860e553438ac35ceaadbc9384bc

commit_message:
Add security headers to web accessable services.

Adds the following headers as static:

    X-Content-Type-Options "nosniff"
    X-XSS-Protection "1; mode=block"
    append Content-Security-Policy "default-src 'self' https: wss:;"

nosniff prevents non-executable mime times from becoming executable.
The X-XSS-Protection header will prevent the loading of a page if the
browser detects an xss attack.  The Content-Security-Policy declares
what dynamic resources are allowed to load.

Adds the following header as user-setable via the
keystone_x_frame_options variable.

    X-Frame-Options "DENY"

- nova-dsvm-full-tempest http://cloudbase-ci.com//nova/489206/7/ : FAILURE in 3h 23m 10s'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2017-10-02 15:56:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

I don't believe we want to try processing traits for both sharing provider and normal providers in the same query. Instead, I think it behooves us to have two separate functions. Let me elaborate.

The caller of these functions will be the code that establishes the allocation candidates. This caller needs to determine the resource providers that either have a particular trait or are associated with a provider that is sharing resources that happens to have a particular trait.

We *could* do the entire thing in a single SQL statement, however the statement will be overly complicated and inefficient for the "normal" cases. Instead, I recommend going with an approach where we have one function for returning the non-sharing resource providers that have *any* of the set of required traits:

 get_providers_with_any_trait(required_traits):

would execute this simple SQL:

 SELECT rpt.resource_provider_id, rpt.trait_id
 FROM resource_provider_traits AS rpt
 WHERE trait_id IN ($required_traits)
 ORDER BY rpt.resource_provider_id

the above SQL will be very fast and efficient since it will be a) satisfied entirely by an index and b) will be guaranteed to be all in memory and in the order already requested in the query.

The get_providers_with_any_trait() function would process the results of the above query into a dict, keyed by resource provider internal ID, containing a set() of trait IDs:

 to_return = collections.defaultdict(set)
 for res in results:
     to_return[res[0]].add(res[1])

A separate function would return the traits that the *sharing providers* have:

 get_sharing_providers_with_any_trait(sharing_provider_ids, required_traits)

which would end up executing this (also very simple) SQL statement:


 SELECT rpt.resource_provider_id, rpt.trait_id
 FROM resource_provider_traits AS rpt
 WHERE trait_id IN ($required_traits)
 AND resource_provider_id IN ($sharing_provider_ids)
 ORDER BY rpt.resource_provider_id

and process into a dict of sets using the same code:'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2017-10-02 16:04:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Sorry, Gerrit save fail.. to continue my review:

 get_sharing_providers_with_any_trait()

would return a dict, keyed by resource provider ID, of a set of traits, like the get_providers_with_any_trait() function:

 to_return = collections.defaultdict(set)
 for res in results:
     to_return[res[0]].add(res[1])

The caller of both get_providers_with_any_trait() and get_sharing_providers_with_any_trait() would then process the returned dicts, winnowing only the non-sharing providers (root providers) that *either* had all the required traits OR when merged with the sharing providers, had all the required traits:

 providers_having_all_traits = set()
 providers_having_some_traits = collections.defaultdict(set)
 for rp_id, provider_traits in root_providers.items():
     if len(provider_traits) == len(required_traits):
         # Provider has all the requested traits already
         providers_having_all_traits.add(rp_id)
         continue
     
     # Find a sharing provider that has the traits that this
     # provider DOESN'T have...
     need_traits = required_traits - provider_traits
     for sharing_rp_id, sharing_traits in sharing_provider_traits.items():
         if need_traits & sharing_traits:
             provider_having_some_traits[rp_id].add(sharing_rp_id)

In that way, we'd build the list of providers in a way that is debuggable and efficient..."}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2017-10-10 09:45:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

@Jay, I will give a try the way you suggested, agree with the debugable and testable problem which I and Chris talk about also. But I'm not very agree with 'inefficient for the "normal" cases'. If there is no shared resource or no required traits, the related code will be skipped. Anyway, let me give a try and see what it is looks like'}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2017-10-12 14:44:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Workflow-1

Another implementation is at https://review.openstack.org/479766'}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2017-10-22 03:32:43.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
placement: the common method to filter resource providers by traits

This patch adds a common method to return a set of resource provider
IDs which has required traits.

Co-Authored-By: leizhang <lei.a.zhang@intel.com>
Partial-implement-blueprint add-trait-support-in-allocation-candidates
Change-Id: I9e4fe3e708229e501cfa10322379937a11a5112b

commit_message:
placement: add traits support to get resource_providers with shared

This patch adds new parameter 'traits' to the _get_all_with_shared()
function. Also filter the results by the return of
'_get_provider_ids_with_required_traits'.

Change-Id: I089d1cec405ebe4a3735ded44706b6b3cff3463f
Partial-implement-blueprint add-trait-support-in-allocation-candidates

commit_message:
consume load_class_by_alias_or_classname from neutron-lib

neutron-lib now contains the load_class_by_alias_or_classname function.
This patch removes the function from neutron and uses it from lib.

NeutronLibImpact

Change-Id: I47ef642fcb3c8ded5eb7ed0a637033c7bcb3632b

commit_message:
use default subnetpool api def from lib

The default subnetpools extension's API definition was added to
neutron-lib with Ib841f3727e758c0c19c9a4a0acd221ecb4081313. This patch
consumes the API definition from lib.

NeutronLibImpact

Change-Id: I48a1a637e9c45499916ade61cc9f38de3278e67e

commit_message:
Implement policy in code (1)

This commit will prepare for implementing policies in code[1].

Once we completed moving all of policies into code base,
we can also change default policy rules via policy.yaml
instead of policy.json and generate policy.yaml by command:
$ tox -e genpolicy

[1]https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/queens/policy-in-code.html

Change-Id: I587ee663eff9632ec355cef8152c13e1ebfffeb5
Co-authored-By: Hieu LE <hieulq@vn.fujitsu.com>

commit_message:
Bypass web server during service setup

When connecting directly to a keystone host during service setup, use
the UWSGI ports instead of going through the web server to avoid any
potential errors with differing URI protocols or SSL certs not including
the hostnames of individual hosts.

Change-Id: Ie5b33f9d0210a23badb63cab72c481b027790be3
Closes-Bug: 1699191

commit_message:
Added nat_source flag for networks.

In some more complex clouds there can not only be more than one valid network
on a server that NAT can attach to, there can also be more than one valid
network from which to get a NAT address. Allow flagging a network so that it
can be found.

Change-Id: I3d8dd6d734a1013d2d4a43e11c3538c3a345820b

commit_message:
Add shade-tox-tips jobs

Breaking shade with changes to os-client-config is bad. Add shade's
unittest jobs that are configured to work against os-client-config
master.

Also move the legacy osc dsvm job here so we can remove it from
project-config.

Change-Id: Ie3e9a4deca1d74b94e810e87e130706fe15fe2c9
Depends-On: I5b411be5c5aa43535fa89a51d6099aadd7a8ea60

commit_message:
move git configuration for release jobs to ansible tasks

Instead of scripting the git configuration, use tasks in pre playbooks
for the jobs. We use different settings for tag-releases and
propose-constraint-updates.

Change-Id: Id3713d89a8b2af821de41a146954be551337cf75
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Warn when configuring dedicated database connection for placement API

The options supporting this are discussed in change
39fb302fd9c8fc57d3e4bea1c60a02ad5067163f, which has since been reverted.
It may be implemented in the future, but currently has no effect.

Change-Id: I63db5b9762d5bdaf6583a4b68c6407f6fbcf33c6
(cherry picked from commit a36977475a293db8cdc9aabd4fb10fd315aff6f6)

commit_message:
Allow setting log files for apache vhost

This allows the setting of the error and access file logs, as well as
the access log format. This was done in a similar fashion as one can
configure these ones in the keystone wsgi manifest.

Change-Id: I0e42e5edacc10060c2906f21fd907845cda203a4

commit_message:
Synchronize ironic and ironicclients list of boot devices

Ensure list of boot devices specified in ironic matches whats
specified in ironicclient. Specifically in this case adding
'wanboot'.

Change-Id: Icd427fc02296cca94ebe722d4cacecb3a902d4c2
Closes-Bug: #1724974
Signed-off-by: Matt Keenan <matt.keenan@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Disable nested virt in base devstack job

We were doing this in devstack-gate. The gate can't handle nested virt.

Change-Id: Ie71663c3144908ddd134fa5a5b1b2d265a60edcf

commit_message:
Automate doc creation as part of init-series

With dynamically generated series index headers, we can now automate the
creation of a new release series' documentation pages.

Change-Id: I9adf48aaf8d78821a73c74e7e5372d7269136270

commit_message:
Add release highlights to deliverables

This adds the ability to provide release highlights in the deliverable
yaml file that get extracted and compiled into a highlights page for
each release.

Change-Id: I1d72f4608f0dd2b11894f918d89be1ad0ad9c8fd

[{'created': '2017-10-21 15:37:11.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Fix branch check for proposal script"

We check out our branches with git directly and do not use
prepolated content. Thus, we do have remote branches here and need this.

This reverts commit 4eeb97c278b70445d0d6bb0a1779282d5aeffd01.

Change-Id: I0fece091a9bdf305d8370899a7e9aa7a21ae05b4
'}]
commit_message:
Revert "Fix branch check for proposal script"

We check out our branches with git directly and do not use
prepolated content. Thus, we do have remote branches here and need this.

This reverts commit 4eeb97c278b70445d0d6bb0a1779282d5aeffd01.

Change-Id: I0fece091a9bdf305d8370899a7e9aa7a21ae05b4

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-21 16:19:27.000000000', 'message': 'Fix flake8

fix a "bug" in that the flake8 configuration in tox.ini was exclusively
selecting H231 as the only error it would report, so it was missing the
errors in the python modules (such as submit_log_processor_jobs). Due to
this being the case for a long time (since 2004) limit the more thorough
linting to the roles/ and playbooks/ directories where we'll be adding
ansible plugins/modules/etc. Also, lint in jenkins/script and nodepool.

Fix problems found.

We can lint everything with pep8 once the zuul v2 scripts are removed,
not worth patching them right now.

Change-Id: I479f010643cf3b67c183d763510f07a33400d38b
Co-Authored-By: Jesse Keating <omgjlk@us.ibm.com>

Fix flake8

fix a "bug" in that the flake8 configuration in tox.ini was exclusively
selecting H231 as the only error it would report, so it was missing the
errors in the python modules (such as submit_log_processor_jobs). Due to
this being the case for a long time (since 2004) limit the more thorough
linting to the roles/ and playbooks/ directories where we'll be adding
ansible plugins/modules/etc. Also, lint in jenkins/script and nodepool.

Fix problems found.

We can lint everything with pep8 once the zuul v2 scripts are removed,
not worth patching them right now.

Change-Id: I479f010643cf3b67c183d763510f07a33400d38b
Co-Authored-By: Jesse Keating <omgjlk@us.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Allow creating security rules without protocol

In order to create a rule for any protocol, the client
must not specify the protocol in the API call. This
is currently impossible because protocol defaults to TCP.

In order not to change the default behavior, a "new" protocol
name is added: "any", which makes this CLI skip sending the
protocol field altogether.

Change-Id: I58853d3745f3631007e5e9780c0c5c2526b730a3
Closes-Bug: 1712242

commit_message:
Initial OSA zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: I7e536835e2af36b6845bf429ed53e9c3713bd848

thx, Doug. For me looks fine. Maybe someone else want's to review before merge."}, {'account_id': 19779, 'date': '2017-10-21 10:28:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Sorry to make you feel bad, I will update this patch for you, bud. If I knew that you didn't have time to update this patch, I would do it for you instead of to comment it. If you like, after this point, I can do something like this for you before your patches merged. :)
By the way, the Contributor Guide is not like other guides, people follows this guide to write. So the patches of this guide, we will be cautious to review and merge. I hope you can understand. Thank you so much for what you have done in documentation, and looking forward to your coming contributions!"}, {'account_id': 19779, 'date': '2017-10-21 10:50:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 19779, 'date': '2017-10-21 10:51:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2017-10-21 13:50:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

> Sorry to make you feel bad, I will update this patch for you, bud.
 > If I knew that you didn't have time to update this patch, I would
 > do it for you instead of to comment it. If you like, after this
 > point, I can do something like this for you before your patches
 > merged. :)
 > By the way, the Contributor Guide is not like other guides, people
 > follows this guide to write. So the patches of this guide, we will
 > be cautious to review and merge. I hope you can understand. Thank
 > you so much for what you have done in documentation, and looking
 > forward to your coming contributions!

I think you missed my point a little. I don't feel bad for having formatting issues. I'm perfectly capable of fixing them and I recognize that having a common style helps reviewers. Having a -1 from Zuul is different from having a -1 from another person, though, and I think *other* contributors may be turned off by nit-picking on things that can't be automatically detected. We can't afford to turn away any contributors for such minor issues. 

In the case of the heading styles for instance, emacs has built-in support for rotating heading levels in rst files that uses a different sequence of styles than has been adopted in the style guide. So, every emacs user has to do something by hand that they normally don't have to think about at all. If they received an error when they ran their local build, that would tell them they need to do that extra work before they even propose the patch.

What I'm trying to do is encourage the team to take the attitude that now that we have far fewer people writing full time, we need to be more lenient with the writing we *do* receive. If it needs to be cleaned up a little, just do that. In cases where formatting can't be caught automatically, I personally think that the best way is to propose a second patch on top of the first, and leave a comment on the original patch saying "This looks good. I made a few changes to meet our style guidelines in a follow up patch at $URL." That tells the original submitter they can go look at the other patch and learn about how to have a more properly formatted patch the next time, but still accepts the effort they have put into the patch they submitted. Smaller changes like trailing white space or missing commas can probably just be added in an update to the original patch.

Ultimately is up to the team to choose an approach. I think the current approach needs to change so reviewers to do what they can to avoid leaving a -1 for reasons other than the actual content being wrong, unclear, or incomplete in some way.'}, {'account_id': 17765, 'date': '2017-10-21 16:38:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2

Let's merge it now."}]

commit_message:
Remove unneeded msgfmt test

The infra scripts run msgfmt since some time, no need to run it here as
well.

This fixes the pep8 failure in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/493290/
since that change removes the remaining po files and now the find fails
since there is no po file anymore.

Change-Id: I6a8b99a9d63e421f4a6eae6f0aab6d0955f7916b

commit_message:
Update upgrade role for Queens from P

This changes the a-r-r with the proper version, and fixes
the repo path for role upgrades:

The role will, during test-upgrade-pre, have its current branch
checked out, and will deploy the current branch infrastructure,
including the generation of the constraints.

Then, the installation of previous branch of the role will use
the constraints for its previous version, but will have no
constraints for it, and fail.

We need to generate the constraints for the previous version too.
This should do it.

This patch also implements an initial set of jobs intended to
match the current job execution method. It does not intend to
improve how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is
currently in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide
the platform to iterate on.

Co-Authored-By: Jean-Philippe Evrard <jean-philippe.evrard@rackspace.co.uk>
Depends-On: I0391ec310c4eede436011a48490e3c524c8ddf4d

commit_message:
Update make_rest_client to work with version discovery

Using make_rest_client on clouds that put unversioned endpoints in the
catalog results in incorrectly set up adapters.

Add the plumbing to get_session_client to pass version args to
keystoneauth. Then use that from make_rest_client.

Change-Id: I69ad746f672ef0b12680e9db3c7b0c691c9f87e4

commit_message:
Add unittest tips jobs

Changes to keystoneauth and os-client-config are deeply important to
shade. Add a job that runs shade's unittests against their master
branches.

Change-Id: I5b411be5c5aa43535fa89a51d6099aadd7a8ea60
Depends-On: Ifa5cc3e335b9e9ad52c4c5c9ab71aaea70d4c9aa

commit_message:
Initial OSA zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: Ib1d06f9862503faa7178fd927287b5ebfc05c900

Set success-url on coverage jobs to cover/

We fetch the coverage reports into the cover directory on logs. The
coverage report is the main thing you want to look at from a coverage
job. Set the url to that.

commit_message:
Fix neutron-lbaas-dashboard to use -horizon jobs

The neutron-lbaas-dashboard project needs to use the -horizon versions
of the openstack-python-jobs, publish-openstack-sphinx-docs, and
publish-to-pypi templates.

commit_message:
Add network availability zone information for network agents

This patch adds the availability zone column for network agents on the system
information page, if either the router_availability_zone or the
network_availability_zone extension is enabled.

Change-Id: Id7509fab440383bff45cb8ce5bdc3f8eb62045f4
Closes-Bug: #1716638

commit_message:
Rename "Import Key Pair" to "Import Public Key"

The text "Import Key Pair" is not accurate technically, using "Import
Public Key" to make more sense.

Change-Id: Ifd313c150cb0ee07c86e5f3834aaee43a0fb801b

commit_message:
Swap the order of interface and endpoint_type

The parameter we should desire is 'interface'. 'endpoint_type' is the
old name. List the non-compliant clients rather than the compliant
clients so that we can more easily track which ones we need to go work
on.

Change-Id: Iedcebc74e14abea49f3bcc087a1ff506520d7183

commit_message:
mk_build_dir: fix and refactor

The current mk_build_dir is buggy: only the result of the creation of
TMP_IMAGE_DIR is checked.

The current implementation of mk_build_dir uses some code
duplications.

This patch fixes both issues.

Change-Id: I96faf432ccd40754af138ace417bf6781c973431
Signed-off-by: Andreas Florath <andreas@florath.net>

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Adds 'sata' as a valid disk bus for qemu and kvm hypervisors

Reasoning:
- Setting custom properties on glance images allows us to select the
type of disk bus e.g. VIRTIO/IDE/SCSI.
Although SATA disk bus works perfectly for qemu/kvm, it is not allowed
due to a check in virt/libvirt/blockinfo.py : is_disk_bus_valid_for_virt
- some Linux (custom) images require use of SATA bus rather than any
other that seems to be allowed.

Change-Id: Ie32ff7acf31d80d4fc1adbeadaaf30a886d10e49
Closes-Bug: #1686136

Remove unecessary playbook

We should be able to set the tox work dir in the job definition.

Also, updates the files matcher so changes to the jobs cause them
to run.

The build times for the usefulness of this patch speaks for itself. The
requirements gate now takes less than 10m, down from over 14m on
average.

commit_message:
Revise cluster/node check action records design

This patch revises cluster/node check action records design, the purpose
is to avoid creating too many action records when we do cluster/node
checking periodically.
And we will not delete check action records which are  from manual operation.

Implements: blueprint improve-action-event

Change-Id: Ia356a6a7e5f3afca5a10b6ca5961c9119012834c

commit_message:
Trivial: fix spelling of allocation_request

Reviews of other patches in this series raised the criticism that the
term 'allocation request' was being used, when the proper name for it
should be 'allocation_request'. I've broken these simple corrections
into a separate patch so as not to clutter up the other patches.

Blueprint: return-alternate-hosts

Change-Id: Idd2b9e3b0000fa8eeb2e0e9c3337b1d99b13ada7

commit_message:
Fixes toggle behavior in Network Topology graphs

Changes the buttons (Toggle Labels and Toggle Network Collapse)
 in the network topology graph view into bootstrap styled checkboxes
(the buttons should now operate as on/off) and modifies the relevant
js code to prevent random un-toggeling on data loading. Additionally,
the states for each button should now be respected on page refresh.

Change-Id: I16c00786a2c7cd37a38ebecc9494861232d2f473
Closes-Bug: 1672723

commit_message:
Fix puppet-openstack_spec_helper for Zuulv3

With Zuulv3, the value of ZUUL_REF is always empty as well as
the value of ZUUL_URL which can shift arguments by one and
cause an issue.

Depends-On: Idd846c569a6e067125e130f189be9ae8ffba1646
Change-Id: I055677ea7664ed488ee1f05193b7fdb7dc5bcb3a
(cherry picked from commit 1374d1055e61e12be9374e197fd7a00cf3a9c2f5)

commit_message:
Implement policy in code (6)

Like oslo.config, with oslo.policy, we can define all of
default rules in code base and only change some rules
via policy file. Another thing that we should use yaml
format instead of json format[1].

This commit will move all default policies to code for:
- actions
- events
- services
- webhooks

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/queens/policy-in-code.html

Change-Id: I0919eb5dc84c0e134b4918f477923b53dc9fbbbb
Co-authored-By: Hieu LE <hieulq@vn.fujitsu.com>

commit_message:
Added type checks for ha device owners

Added owner check types to is_interface function calls
used by templates to decide if the 'delete interface'
button should be displayed or not.

commit_message:
Correct the subnets quota check in admin networks panel

Currently when checking the subnets quota in admin networks table,
the current tenant subnets quota is checked, while the subnet is
created, using the tenant of the selected network[1], this doesn't
look the same. Similarly, in the network details subnets table,
the creation of subnets actions lacks quota checking.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/horizon/blob/master/openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/networks/subnets/workflows.py#L75

Change-Id: Ifb88b97168fc4f500e4bb15658f96363ddc7651f
Closes-Bug:#1719606

Hi Dean, thanks for your review.

>  if val is not None:

It looked good, but the command got the following error after I modified like it.

   update() got an unexpected keyword argument 'force'

In openstackclient(v1), there is 'force' option with 'false' as defualt value.
The original code or your above code treats 'false' as valid value.
It cause openstackclient misjudege and pass 'force' to update() in glanceclient,
which only accepts options including UPDATE_PARAMS, and cause this TypeError.
'force' is not in UPDATE_PARAMS, it shouldn't be passed to update().

   --------glanceclient/v1/images.py----------
   UPDATE_PARAMS = ('name', 'disk_format', 'container_format', 'min_disk',
                    'min_ram', 'owner', 'size', 'is_public', 'protected',
                    'location', 'checksum', 'copy_from', 'properties',
                    # NOTE(bcwaldon: an attempt to update 'deleted' will be
                    # ignored, but we need to support it for backwards-
                    # compatibility with the legacy client library
                    'deleted')
   -------------------------------------------

For your information, I had following tries.

   if val is not None: --> NG("update() got an unexpected keyword argument 'force'" occurs)
   if val or val == 0: --> NG("update() got an unexpected keyword argument 'force'" occurs)
   if val or val is 0: --> OK'}, {'account_id': 23982, 'date': '2017-09-29 09:39:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2017-09-29 18:46:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

This looks like a case where we are handling the option incorrectly then.  The point of the check is to determine if the option is present on the command-line, and the setting of --force to False as a default breaks our ability to do that.  I think we need to change --force to default to None, and ensure inside take_action() that we handle that as False internally as necessary.

Checking for a 0 directly is just as incorrect as False,   Since we have no other way to detect the absense of an option on the command line, we are not (in this case) able to use argparse default values in the manner that -force does.  FWIW, we also have this issue in other APIs and this is why we handle other opposing pairs of options the way we do (see https://docs.openstack.org/python-openstackclient/latest/contributor/command-options.html#boolean-options), like --enable|--disable.  In this case, there is no --no-force option but otherwise it must be handled the same.'}, {'account_id': 23982, 'date': '2017-10-05 05:30:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-10-05 07:19:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Accept 0 for --min-disk and --min-ram

The current openstackclient implementation cannot accept 0
for --min-disk and --min-ram with the "openstack image set" command.
If theses options get set to 0, the option parser in openstackclient
wrongly interprets 0 as no option value. The 0 is valid for these
options if administrators want to make it the default(no minimum
requirements).

This patch fix the parser so that it avoids only 'None'.

Change-Id: Ie8ee37484c02c26f54adc56263fcd167c0ce7eb3
Closes-bug: #1719499

commit_message:
Hide IPv6-addresses when assigning floating IP addresses

A floating IP can only be associated with an IPv4 address, so we should
not show IPv6 addresses in the list of ports when assigning floating IP
addresses.

Change-Id: I7b39a263445204a9efbc8fe113cc79146d9bee8c
Closes-Bug: #1703360
Closes-Bug: #1724393

Memoized caches function specifies use tuples as parameters because
lists are not hashable. When the get_security_groups function is called,
the list type parameter is passed in, this causing fail to use memoized

Closes-Bug:#1712582

commit_message:
Fix UnhashableKeyWarning when calling get_security_groups function

Memoized caches function specifies use tuples as parameters because
lists are not hashable. When the get_security_groups function is called,
the list type parameter is passed in, this causing fail to use memoized
and the console appears UnhashableKeyWarning.

Change-Id: Idc1262c714c3a6a451753286d6b414a27f6cb2cc
Closes-Bug:#1712582

commit_message:
Replace deprecated alias 'os' with 'os_primary'

Tempest has deprecated the alias 'os' and will use the alias 'os_primary'
instead. The alias 'os' was deprecated in Pike and planned to be removed
in Queen.

Let's use the stable alias 'os_primary' for primary credential. This will
help Tempest to remove the deprecated alias 'os'.

Change-Id: I39c33acb6dc33d245c8452d1587c09b31178d728

commit_message:
Avoid deleting parent backup failed caused by 404

Catch NotFound exception in for loop, to avoid dropping out
while deleting parent backup that has multiple children backups.

Change-Id: Idab9fc8d6c09b0b58015b0b9fdf99811d075191f
Closes-bug: #1718572

commit_message:
Add deliverables info

neutron-vpnaas-dashboard is now not a TC-governed project,
so we don't have an entry in openstack/releases, but deliverable files
in openstack/releases are useful for tracking releases and
we can leverage release tools like 'new-release' from the releases repo.

This commit adds deliverable files to the repo.

Change-Id: I3caeecff393d491637231738f06533082c816dd0

commit_message:
Load plugins during the API initialization

It is the first thing that you should do if you would like to use
rally.api programmatically and that's going to be hard to figure out
for new rally users

So let's just load them.

Use rally.api in osresources script

Change-Id: Ib842537e6732bb6f4ae4bf333594fc14bcfeaf53

commit_message:
Update tests to do not use deprecated test.services()

Function 'tempest.test.services()' has moved to
'tempest.common.utils.services()' in version 'Pike'.

commit_message:
update docs to use nova_metadata_host

nova_metadata_ip is deprecated in favor of nova_metadata_host. This
patch updates our docs to use the latter matching our intent on removing
the former.

NOTE: I faced the warning message of this option on Pike also.
It would be great to avoid it for Pike users based on the docs.

Change-Id: I6a8e76acc2f01541f92123e46987b0f2f0fbf1cd
Closes-Bug: #1669955
(cherry picked from commit e7c75d180ba050f76ac414f249b38b5b22c1b42a)

commit_message:
Initial OSA zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: Ie8b995b690e3e3b5da1f777584d8a76a374fc0a9

commit_message:
Add commonly used repositories to required projects

Zuul is able to more effectively clone the roles used in
role tests more reliably that using a standard git clone
because it has a cache implementation to do exactly that.

This implements the commonly used role repositories as
required-projects for the tests so that our playbook to
get the ansible-role-requirements deoesn't have to do
the cloning, it'll just do the right symlinking. It will
still fetch any missing repositories, so this list does
not have to be a *full* list - just enough to help reduce
the current failures due to git cloning problems.

Change-Id: I203dce5ea87feed7c4354039f035742c9c3a5f36
(cherry picked from commit 394c2d7bb38959fdecc70bf5d50dea99a11aa4e0)

commit_message:
Remove doc todo related to bug/1506667

As the bug report 1506667, the bug has been fixed already since 2016-11-22.
In addition, the bug is just kind of reminder to avoid forgetting to
include example config files of upstream in ubuntu packages.
That[1] makes readers confused, so let's just remove it.

[1]: https://docs.openstack.org/nova/pike/install/controller-install-ubuntu.html#install-and-configure-components

Change-Id: I793d58dbc6bad097c772f7715430e75d74521253
Related-bug: #1506667

Spec: Amphora Maintenance Mode

Allow admins to put amphorae into maintenance mode to "freeze" them.

Change-Id: I691414c9abfd2e73f34c7ddcee3637453f409e32
Story: 2001221

commit_message:
[task] Rework junit-xml exporter

* show different tasks results separately
* fix calculations

PS: module rally.common.io.junit will be removed as soon as we clean CLI
layer from old formats.

Change-Id: Id950615e4e3f873d7928678278c030211e7cc998
Closes-Bug: #1711082

commit_message:
Routers can be created with availability zone

When 'availability_zone'-extension is enabled, we present the user with
a drop-down menu containing a list of available availability zones.
This sets the 'availability_zone_hints' parameter on router creation.

Change-Id: I96293202ddd855823e89c4c7ba0b1f6a6423aab2
Partial-bug: #1716638

commit_message:
Add commonly used repositories to required projects

Zuul is able to more effectively clone the roles used in
role tests more reliably that using a standard git clone
because it has a cache implementation to do exactly that.

This implements the commonly used role repositories as
required-projects for the tests so that our playbook to
get the ansible-role-requirements deoesn't have to do
the cloning, it'll just do the right symlinking. It will
still fetch any missing repositories, so this list does
not have to be a *full* list - just enough to help reduce
the current failures due to git cloning problems.

Change-Id: I203dce5ea87feed7c4354039f035742c9c3a5f36
(cherry picked from commit 394c2d7bb38959fdecc70bf5d50dea99a11aa4e0)

commit_message:
Add openstack-ansible-linters job

Currently the linters test is in the project-config
repository, but those are meant to be used for standard
jobs which do not require any repository other than the
one given. Our lint tests use the 'openstack-ansible-tests'
repository, so we should rather use our own job definition.

Change-Id: I0391ec310c4eede436011a48490e3c524c8ddf4d
(cherry picked from commit 0b13f4993f7b0fce08f8aeaba66950f4267e364f)

commit_message:
clean up _one_shard_cycle state machine

* break out per broker handling from _one_shard_cycle to
  _process_broker

* make _process_broker the one place where sharding states
  are transitioned

Change-Id: I3b65e8988bcde697cc286e274ccc41c2671f1937

We need to add openstack ansible information in the role
metadata to be able to track role maturity. With it,
we can create a role maturity table and take decisions about
role deprecations.

The role status isn't "complete" because no functional test

'}]
commit_message:
Add OpenStack-Ansible metadata

We need to add openstack ansible information in the role
metadata to be able to track role maturity. With it,
we can create a role maturity table and take decisions about
role deprecations.

The role status isn't "complete" because no functional test
of the role has been implemented.

Change-Id: I0657a991aa5a3f2493c68044327ef3885d73485e

commit_message:
Emit deprecation warning for federated domain/project APIs

Before the identity API documentation lived in-tree, it lived in the
openstack/keystone-specs project. Before that it lived in it's own
identity-api repository. A long time ago we merged a patch [0] to that
project to deprecate the project and domain APIs in the federation
path. That documentation has since been copied and migrated to the
keystone-specs repository and now keystone itself.

Even though we've deprecated those API in the documentation, we never
formally deprecated them in code using ``versionutils``. This commit
does that. Now a message will be logged anytime that API is used
instead of GET /auth/domains or GET /auth/projects. This makes the
implementation of keystone consistent with documentation we merged
ages ago.

[0] If0c010119512d6a159ce82147a87c4698205a648

Change-Id: I88cb587c7cd69fef400b2eaf7dffda655355b710

commit_message:
Migrate to Zuul v3

Migrate all functional jobs and gate to zuul v3.
We will have to migrate all other legacy jobs too later.
This patch do step 1 in the docs: Move Legacy Jobs to Projects.

diff:
- do not port elasticsearch check
- remove jobs unrelated to branch
- cleanup telemetry-integration gate

Co-Authored-By: gord chung <gord@live.ca>
Co-Authored-By: Dai Dang Van <daidv@vn.fujitsu.com>
Change-Id: Idf49c523c1d0632e8d095e4804817e7b5e772902
(cherry picked from commit cc7950c86fed77e3395504530ac5dd116b4b4e5b)

commit_message:
console: introduce basic framework for security proxying

Introduce a framework to the websocketproxy to allow a security
negotiation to take place between the proxy and the target service,
prior to connecting the client tenant to the target service.

Based on earlier work by Solly Ross <sross@redhat.com>

Change-Id: Ifb9360be73864ab45129c758bd1323a9bab8e48c
Co-authored-by: Stephen Finucane <sfinucan@redhat.com>
Implements: bp websocket-proxy-to-host-security

commit_message:
Remove double $PROJECT from translation publishing

The new publish-artifacts-to-fileserver always adds the projectname, so
remove it here to not have two project names like
tarballs.openstack.org/translation-source/oslo.db/oslo.db

Change-Id: I8d2cf17d4c7500b09ed14ba9be100cb14149a5d3

[{'created': '2017-06-26 03:31:02.000000000', 'message': 'Wrong load removed node of galera cluster.
trove/common/strategies/cluster/experimental/galera_common/api.py.
Method "shrink" in class GaleraCommonCluster,when use DBInstance.find_all
should set argument deleted=False, otherwise it may missing raise a
ClusterShrinkMustNotLeaveClusterEmpty exception.
Same problem at galera_common/taskmanager.py. Method "shrink_cluster" in
GaleraCommonClusterTasks, call DBInstance.findall() with deleted=False
to exclude deleted nodes and that can avoid a NotFound error.

commit_message:
Wrong load removed node of galera cluster.

trove/common/strategies/cluster/experimental/galera_common/api.py.
Method "shrink" in class GaleraCommonCluster,when use DBInstance.find_all
should set argument deleted=False, otherwise it may missing raise a
ClusterShrinkMustNotLeaveClusterEmpty exception.
Same problem at galera_common/taskmanager.py. Method "shrink_cluster" in
GaleraCommonClusterTasks, call DBInstance.findall() with deleted=False
to exclude deleted nodes and that can avoid a NotFound error.

Change-Id: Ibb377630b830da06485fc17a1a723dc1055d9b01
Closes-Bug: 1699953

subject: Remove inexistent option in install guide.

commit_message:
Migrate to Zuul v3

Migrate all functional jobs and gate to zuul v3.
We will have to migrate all other legacy jobs too later.
This patch do step 1 in the docs: Move Legacy Jobs to Projects.

diff:
- do not port elasticsearch check
- remove jobs unrelated to branch
- cleanup telemetry-integration gate

Co-Authored-By: gord chung <gord@live.ca>
Co-Authored-By: Dai Dang Van <daidv@vn.fujitsu.com>
Change-Id: Idf49c523c1d0632e8d095e4804817e7b5e772902
(cherry picked from commit cc7950c86fed77e3395504530ac5dd116b4b4e5b)

commit_message:

refs/heads from ZUUL_REFNAME so that the script continues to work.

commit_message:
Use skipTest() method instead of deprecated skip()

The method for skipping a test in unittest is skipTest(). testtools also
provides skip(), but that is deprecated. This eliminates the deprecation
warnings by switching to the recommended skipTest().

Change-Id: I45da95958e6f65475beab0d7a3c6de6604fa82d7

commit_message:
Add commonly used repositories to required projects

Zuul is able to more effectively clone the roles used in
role tests more reliably that using a standard git clone
because it has a cache implementation to do exactly that.

This implements the commonly used role repositories as
required-projects for the tests so that our playbook to
get the ansible-role-requirements deoesn't have to do
the cloning, it'll just do the right symlinking. It will
still fetch any missing repositories, so this list does
not have to be a *full* list - just enough to help reduce
the current failures due to git cloning problems.

Change-Id: I203dce5ea87feed7c4354039f035742c9c3a5f36
(cherry picked from commit 394c2d7bb38959fdecc70bf5d50dea99a11aa4e0)

commit_message:
Add openstack-ansible-linters job

Currently the linters test is in the project-config
repository, but those are meant to be used for standard
jobs which do not require any repository other than the
one given. Our lint tests use the 'openstack-ansible-tests'
repository, so we should rather use our own job definition.

Change-Id: I0391ec310c4eede436011a48490e3c524c8ddf4d
(cherry picked from commit 0b13f4993f7b0fce08f8aeaba66950f4267e364f)

commit_message:
Initial OSA zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: I30fc9d929c27ee0d0b460a87a0029cbc87f3ccd8

commit_message:
Remove unified queue from gate pipeline

Initially the intent for adding this was to better test
any patches for roles together before they merge, but it
has had the unintended side-effect of causing patches to
take much longer to merge (because they all get lined up
in a single queue, rather than independent queues) and
a lot more infra resources are used (because a patch
that fails at the top of the queue will result in all
subsequent patches restarting all their tests).

As discussed in the channel, we'd prefer to revert back
to the previous independent queue method of testing. It
has served us well.

Change-Id: I88334fd6e763b8cdce975e092958c9735d00ab9d

commit_message:
Make playbook includes dynamic

By default the includes are static, which means that all the tasks in
the include get the when applied rather than the include itself. This
leads to all tasks getting evaluated and needing to make sure variables
are defined, even though we are skipping all the tasks.

Instead, we make these includes dynamic, so that the skip happens at
the include, and ansible never evaluates any of the tasks if the
include is skipped.

Change-Id: Ia7df40e8005d4b9261caf3d15d34ff895ef99013

commit_message:
Initial OSA zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: Ib7c21d5e48f975bb8effe66bf7f4c305d70a71e4

rally: rework plugin

add argument to call of scenario.configure
use classes for scenarions instead of methods
change client for describe images

commit_message:
Improve test coverage of the fetch-zuul-cloner role and the shim

This tests that we are indeed able to use the zuul cloner shim
and that it works as expected with and without required projects.

commit_message:
Allow re-negotiation of the latest version supplied by CLI

Currently --os-baremetal-api-version=latest results in the latest known API
version being send to the server. This does not work, if the server is older
than the client. This patch enables the version to be downgraded to the latest
server version in this case.

Change-Id: I3c48b3dbfef9ff3ee6001d27c8e1eb04341e98ec
Partial-Bug: #1671145

commit_message:
Clarify backlog instructions and add ideas dir

One of the outcomes of the Pike retrospective to clarification
of the purpose of backlog. It was also mentioned that it would be
useful to have an `ideas` directory that allow people to propose
ideas that need to be freshed out and discussed. The backlog somewhat
filled this purpose but is going to be more specific in the future.

This commit clears up the direction of each location and what purpose
they fill.

Change-Id: Ie07f11e67aef1e03311c430963938fe079bf0fa6

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-09-19 16:29:17.000000000', 'message': '(WIP)DVR: Fix unbound fip port migration to bound port

With the current change in allowing the unbound fip
to be associated with the snat node, we are seeing
that all floating IPs that are associated with an
unbound port are created at the snat node.
This is also applicable for floating IPs that are
created just before associating the port to a VM.
We have seen such scenarios in the test cases.

This is the right behavior as per design. But when
the port is bound to a host, the floating IP should
be migrated to the respective host.

This patch fixes the issue by sending notification to
the respective node, when the port is bound and also
clear the fip from the snat node.

Change-Id: I6b1f3ffc3c3336035632f6a82d3a87b3be57b403

commit_message:
DVR: Fix unbound fip port migration to bound port

With the current change in allowing the unbound fip
to be associated with the snat node, we are seeing
that all floating IPs that are associated with an
unbound port are created at the snat node.
This is also applicable for floating IPs that are
created just before associating the port to a VM.
We have seen such scenarios in the test cases.

This is the right behavior as per design. But when
the port is bound to a host, the floating IP should
be migrated to the respective host.

This patch fixes the issue by sending notification to
the respective node, when the port is bound and also
clear the fip from the snat node.

Closes-Bug: #1718788
Change-Id: I6b1f3ffc3c3336035632f6a82d3a87b3be57b403

commit_message:
Initial OSA zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: Id3316aca00173bc55428f8f1987765b17d4de200

commit_message:
Use synchronize to upload to static site

The copy module does not scale well to hundreds+ of files, so
switch to rsync instead.

Change-Id: I35a006096fcded5c8e2c74d1908597e064312e04

commit_message:
Rename auth_uri to www_authenticate_uri

The [keystone_authtoken]/auth_uri middleware parameter has been causing
extreme confusion amongst operators and developers ever since the
keystonemiddleware started accepting keystoneauth plugin parameters
including auth_url. The two parameters look identical and yet have
completely different meanings and are both required. This patch
deprecates auth_uri and renames it to www_authenticate_uri, which more
accurately describes the WWW-Authenticate header it is configuring and
is dissimilar to any other keystone_authtoken middleware parameter. This
also renames the internal variable names for consistency with the config
option.

Change-Id: I0cf11da3d395749df28077427689fdafc8a6b981

Fix publish jobs

Add missing "/" to html so that we really publish to
https://developer.openstack.org/api-ref/baremetal/
instead of as currently to

commit_message:
Move to dictionary list of projects zuul._projects

Zuul exports the projects list as a dictionary in _projects in the
depends-on.  The idea is that we switch these jobs to that, and do
some testing.  When ready, we switch "projects" to be the dictionary
view, and revert "_project" calls here to "project".

Change-Id: I430277369f9ecb2ecc0a31f795c72bba83bcecff

commit_message:
Skip openstack-tox-py35 jobs on release deliverables

Unit tests do not need to run when requesting new deliverables in the
releases repo. Skip the job if that's all there is.

Change-Id: I5050ebaad78ff4942322e3ccd86a89b723315111

commit_message:
Refactor Ironic and Ironic Inspector services

Turn Ironic and Ironic Inspector API services functions into thunks
so the store and dispatch is easily passed, this allows to use auth
selectors for service url and auth token id

commit_message:
Disable Tempest cleanup till Tempest moves to Keystone V3

* Due to this bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/tempest/+bug/1659065
  Tempest cleanup does not work with v3 api, we need to fix it.
  In order to unblock the gates, we need to disable this currently.

Change-Id: Id9849dd2121977418372edcbfdfbbfc8bf2fab27

commit_message:
Allow containerized undercloud deploy with SELinux

When SELinux is enforcing, use :Z flag for the heat_all
container's volumes. Note, if a volume mount with a Z,
then the label will be specific to the container, and
not be able to be shared between containers.

Partial-bug: #1682179
Related-bug: #1723003

Change-Id: Ib4022e022eb2b757591635c362b572ab06f65ed8
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobreli@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Huawei: Mask chap password in log

Users won't see the chap password shown in the
log for safety consideration, so we will mask it
in the log.

SecurityImpact
Closes-Bug: #1535706
Change-Id: I3835d7364cc3c96c38c917fc0fb1674a11447954

commit_message:
Reduce redundant code in Storwize SVC tests

Currently there is duplicated code located in different test classes.
This patch reorganizes the classes to reduce some redundant code.
Also this patch changes the vairable names 'iscsi_driver' and
'fc_driver' to 'driver'.

Change-Id: I97e660202c25200e1e698e75b9ccb8871a751548

commit_message:
RBD: allow a missing parent in delete operations

In the scenario where a volume is created from another volume, there
exists a parent dependency that must be cleaned up when the cloned
volume is deleted.  It is possible for a concurrent parent delete
operation to race here, and the parent volume may no longer exist.  If
this is the case, allow the delete operation to proceed since the work
has already been done.

Change-Id: Ib0fc5a10366eedae31e2431c4a7c90ecf9cbe954
Closes-Bug: #1641518

commit_message:
Add validation for Huawei driver configuration

Some configurations of Huawei driver aren't validated right now,
this patch addes the necessary validations.

Change-Id: Ie912142444d41805201b791caf5736611f9cd680
Closes-Bug: #1636048

commit_message:
Add OpenStack-Ansible metadata

We need to add openstack ansible information in the role
metadata to be able to track role maturity. With it,
we can create a role maturity table and take decisions about
role deprecations.

Change-Id: I8641ad42f16280456328da8529627bf4e9e3c4e6

commit_message:
Cleanup mount / umount and associated rmdir calls

Add a new filesytem mounting helper in privsep, and then start
moving things across to it. This currently implements mount and
unmount. We get to cleanup some rmdir calls while we're at it
which is nice as well.

I've added an upgrade note mentioning that we no longer ignore
the value of stderr from mount calls, as requesed in code review.

Change-Id: Ib5e585fa4bfb99617cd3ca983674114d323a3cce
blueprint: hurrah-for-privsep

commit_message:
Add OpenStack-Ansible metadata

We need to add openstack ansible information in the role
metadata to be able to track role maturity. With it,
we can create a role maturity table and take decisions about
role deprecations.

Change-Id: Ib86d99a78a97e0cc38941c366a72d299af724f88

commit_message:
Add openstack-ansible-linters job

Currently the linters test is in the project-config
repository, but those are meant to be used for standard
jobs which do not require any repository other than the
one given. Our lint tests use the 'openstack-ansible-tests'
repository, so we should rather use our own job definition.

Change-Id: I0391ec310c4eede436011a48490e3c524c8ddf4d

commit_message:
Add commonly used repositories to required projects

Zuul is able to more effectively clone the roles used in
role tests more reliably that using a standard git clone
because it has a cache implementation to do exactly that.

This implements the commonly used role repositories as
required-projects for the tests so that our playbook to
get the ansible-role-requirements deoesn't have to do
the cloning, it'll just do the right symlinking. It will
still fetch any missing repositories, so this list does
not have to be a *full* list - just enough to help reduce
the current failures due to git cloning problems.

commit_message:
tripleo: index /var/log/*.log.txt files

Right now, we only index logstash.txt, which is fine now. The file is
~100K.
But this file doesn't context OpenStack services logs, and other logs
we want to index, so we can use elastic-recheck more powerfully.

So this patch index both undercloud & subnodes (overcloud) .log.txt
files present in /var/log/*.

Change-Id: Id5b9be6130e4e4506418a254a5e57e105fa4d03c

Add ansible-role-k8s-(keystone|mariadb)

commit_message:
playbooks: os-lxc-container-setup: Only stop the container if it's running

Sometimes, despite the container being started by the
lxc_container_create role, we may find it stopped when we try to
restart it as we see in the following error

TASK [Lxc container restart] ***************************************************
Thursday 12 October 2017  16:56:03 +0000 (0:00:03.191)       2:11:34.445 ******
FAILED - RETRYING: Lxc container restart (3 retries left).
FAILED - RETRYING: Lxc container restart (2 retries left).
FAILED - RETRYING: Lxc container restart (1 retries left).
fatal: [controller00_horizon_container-a0c1ea76 -> 172.29.236.11]:
FAILED! => {"attempts": 3, "changed": true, "cmd": ["lxc-stop", "--name", "controller00_horizon_container-a0c1ea76", "--logfile",
"/var/log/lxc/lxc-controller00_horizon_container-a0c1ea76.log", "--logpriority", "INFO", "-t 10"], "delta": "0:00:00.019918", "end":
"2017-10-12 16:56:41.885367", "failed": true, "rc": 2, "start": "2017-10-12 16:56:41.865449", "stderr": "controller00_horizon_container-a0c1ea76 is not running",
"stderr_lines": ["controller00_horizon_container-a0c1ea76 is not running"], "stdout": "", "stdout_lines": []}

It's not exactly clear why the container stopped by itself so lets try
to workaround this by simply checking if the container is actually
running before we try to stop it. If the container is still in an unusable
state, then the lxc-start command that follows this task will fail anyway.

Change-Id: I179f9f5dd08c74eaa88666dc19698fcb348703eb

commit_message:
Initial OSA zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: I8924694d0ff88ecb009b3c16b7ab869c35364c2e

commit_message:
Stop trying to set MTU on LXC bridge interface

This setting is invalid on the bridge and prevents it
from coming up. The bridge uses the lowest MTU used by
all of its connected ports automatically, so any MTU
configured for LXC containers will be used by the bridge.

Change-Id: I8ba8c43492493c4de46469903f0567b6ca7b509d
Closes-Bug: 1724337

commit_message:
Support manage_firewall during deprecation period

This is a follow-up on If83db978080b9c4e5d51ba50bbe8ed26e29abe83: allow
folks to use:

  [firewall]
  manage_firewall = False

to disable the (default) iptables driver during the deprecation period of
the [firewall] option group.  This effectively sets the pxe_filter.driver
to noop.

Change-Id: Idcbc457fffeb1c4bd7c1c747e870b53e2e167d55

commit_message:
Initial OSA zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

Change-Id: I56450a9ad8f4e3ad28a92e3e0272f40fbd726dc0

Switch openstack-tox-cover to parent tox-cover

Currently the coverage job output is not being collected.
This patch switches the openstack-tox-cover job to parent from tox-cover
and adds the OpenStack requirements/constraints from openstack-tox.

commit_message:
jenkins-jobs: enable nova novnc proxy with TLS

Enable the nova novnc proxy service and tell devstack to configure it
for using TLS to the compute nodes

Change-Id: I433fb702209d87d43699cb54f936039da1865dd6
Implements bp: websocket-proxy-to-host-security
Depends-on: Ib29d3f5f18533115b9c51e27b373e92fc0a28d1a

Add attributes schema for OS::Keystone::Project

Add `attributes_schema` and `_resolve_attribute` for
OS::Keystone::Project. This patch allow get_attr works

Clean out old mariadb apt sources

Cleans out old mariadb apt sources before
running redeploy to prevent issues during
leap frog with galera client.

commit_message:
Non-leaders set allowed_units down shared-db rel

The allowed_units key needs to be set by all units rather than
just the leader incase the leader dies and the setting is lost.

Change-Id: I0ed687e5615ee1de5ea34c9169e2728fe557886b

commit_message:
[glance] mesure upload data to the image

In Glance V2 creation of image and upload a data to it are separate
actions. Let's add action timer for upload action as well.

Change-Id: Ia733b5f7e67eec91bf7f8ca7c522037b3c140817
Closes-Bug: #1607775

Question (maybe stupid as I'm still familiarizing myself): In a HA environment with multiple keystones and asymmetric encryption/signing, could we encrypt the token with multiple public keys and therefore allow the multiple keystones to have different private keys?"}, {'account_id': 5046, 'date': '2017-10-13 18:22:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> Question (maybe stupid as I'm still familiarizing myself): In a HA
 > environment with multiple keystones and asymmetric
 > encryption/signing, could we encrypt the token with multiple public
 > keys and therefore allow the multiple keystones to have different
 > private keys?

That gets interesting.. because each keystone node should have it's own private key. Every other keystone node in the deployment would need a copy of every keystone's public key. That would allow keystone-1 to issue a token that can be decrypted by keystone-2 and keystone-3."}, {'account_id': 17860, 'date': '2017-10-13 18:28:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1
